   <head>EPIGRAM XIV.</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="sestet">
     <l n="1" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">TOM thought a wild profusion great:</l>
     <l n="2" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">And therefore spent his whole estate:</l>
     <l n="3" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Will thinks the wealthy are ador'd,</l>
     <l n="4" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">And gleans what misers blush to hoard.</l>
     <l n="5" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">Their passion, merit, fate the same,</l>
     <l n="6" met="-+|-+|-+|-+" line_length="8">They thirst and starve alike for fame.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
  </body>
